Ivory Coast’s National Statistics Institute has said that the consumer price inflation rose to 1.8 percent year-on-year in November, up from 0.8 percent in October 2018. It also said that food and soft drink prices increased to 2.1 percent year-on-year, while housing and utilities prices jumped 6.9 percent adding that transport costs rose by 1.7 percent. Ivory Coast’s economy accounts for around 40 percent of the eight-nation West African CFA franc currency zone.